---
scope: src/components/Expo
description: Expo mascot — fixed bottom-right sprite with scroll-contextual speech bubble tips driven by IntersectionObserver.
intent: >
  Expo is the site's resident domain expert. Its dual job is to personify the
  AIDE methodology (Domain Expert framing) and to surface scroll-contextual
  guidance as the visitor moves through the marketing sections. A tip and pose
  keyed to the current visible section appear in a speech bubble pinned to the
  fixed sprite. Expo is ambient, never intrusive: it never blocks content, never
  auto-opens after the visitor dismisses it, and never reads like a chatbot.
  Clicking the sprite after dismissal re-opens the bubble, giving the visitor
  control at all times.
outcomes:
  desired:
    - Pose and tip string are resolved from EXPO_TIPS keyed on the active SectionId from ExpoTipContext; switching sections updates both without a page reload.
    - The bubble is dismissed per-session on close; it never auto-opens a second time after dismissal. Clicking the sprite toggles the bubble back on.
    - "The mascot wrapper is positioned fixed bottom-right (bottom: 24px, right: 24px, z-index: 20) with pointer-events-none so underlying page content remains fully clickable."
    - The page-level floating sprite renders at 140px wide; a sidebar variant renders at 58px wide.
    - The speech bubble is 280px wide with a right-bottom arrow; it appears and disappears without layout shift.
    - No string anywhere in this module — component names, alt text, speech bubble title, inline comments in shipped files — says "AIDEY" or uses "AID" as a standalone mascot name.
  undesired:
    - Chatbot UX — the mascot is ambient guidance, not a conversational interface. No input field, no send button, no chat history.
    - The mascot wrapper intercepting pointer events and blocking clicks on underlying content (pointer-events-none on the wrapper is load-bearing).
    - Any tip title or body string containing "AIDEY", "aidey", or standalone "AID" as a mascot name.
    - Layout shift when the speech bubble appears or disappears (dimensions must not push sibling content).
---

## Context

Expo is the Domain Expert personification of the AIDE methodology. The name is not arbitrary — AIDE is a double entendre for Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering and AI Domain Expert, and Expo occupies the Domain Expert half on the site. Shipping the bubble with any reference to "AIDEY" (the design-handoff draft name) or the interim "AID" would undo this positioning: the visitor would come away with no coherent brand signal for who the mascot is.

The mascot must be ambient. Marketing pages are already dense with interactive elements (pipeline stage selector, intent-tree, vault-brain tabs, CLI demo). Expo is additive context — a hint about what the visible section means — not a feature that demands attention. The non-blocking constraint (pointer-events-none on the wrapper) is therefore structural, not cosmetic: a fixed element that intercepts clicks anywhere in the bottom-right quadrant actively breaks the page for visitors who scroll to that area.

The scroll-contextual tip system works through a shared context (`ExpoTipContext`) that holds the `activeSection` SectionId. Section wrapper components (`SectionObserver`) use IntersectionObserver to call `setActiveSection` when their section enters the viewport threshold. Expo reads `activeSection` and resolves the matching tip from `EXPO_TIPS`. This decouples the mascot from the section layout: the mascot never knows which component is on screen, only which `SectionId` is active.

## Strategy

**Tip resolution is a pure lookup.** `EXPO_TIPS[activeSection]` yields the tip and pose. No derivation, no fallback chain, no string interpolation. The lookup is guaranteed to succeed because `EXPO_TIPS` is typed as `Record<SectionId, ExpoTip>` — every `SectionId` has an entry.

**Dismissal state lives in `ExpoTipContext`, not in the Expo component.** This keeps the dismissed flag accessible to any future consumer (e.g. a docs sidebar variant) without prop drilling. Default is `false` (visible). Once set to `true`, it is never reset automatically — only by user interaction (clicking the sprite).

**pointer-events-none on the wrapper; pointer-events-auto on the bubble and sprite only.** The fixed wrapper covers a corner of the viewport. Without `pointer-events: none` on the wrapper, the covered area becomes a click dead zone for any underlying content. The bubble and sprite button need `pointer-events: auto` to remain interactive.

**Float animation runs on the sprite at all times.** The `expoFloat` keyframe (already in globals.css) runs 4s ease-in-out infinite. It applies to the sprite image, not the bubble, so the bubble does not bob when visible. The animation plays even when the bubble is dismissed — the floating sprite signals that something interactive is there.

**Speech bubble arrow is a rotated square pseudo-element positioned at right-bottom.** A 12×12 box rotated -45deg, positioned -6px from the right edge and 22px from the bottom, creates the pointing arrow. The bubble background (`var(--color-card)`) and border (`1px solid var(--color-border)`) both apply to the arrow element so it blends seamlessly.

**The speech bubble does not use a portal.** It renders as a sibling of the sprite button inside the fixed wrapper. Fixed positioning on the wrapper handles viewport anchoring; the bubble does not need its own stacking context.

## Good examples

A correctly rendered Expo mascot on the hero section:

```
                        ┌────────────────────────────────────┐
                        │ hey — i'm Expo              ×      │
                        │                                     │
                        │ your domain expert. i walk you      │
                        │ through how intent becomes code,    │
                        │ one stage at a time.                │
                        │                              ▲      │
                        └────────────────────────────────────┘
                                                     [sprite]
```

The `×` button is in the top-right corner. The arrow points down-right toward the sprite. The sprite floats gently. Clicking anywhere in the page content area behind the mascot still registers (pointer-events-none wrapper).

After dismissal, the sprite floats alone in the bottom-right corner. Clicking it re-opens the bubble for the current section.

## Bad examples

A mascot wrapper with `pointer-events: auto` (the default) that intercepts clicks on page content behind the bottom-right corner — any link, button, or interactive element in that area becomes unreachable until the user scrolls away.

A speech bubble title reading "AIDEY says: the .aide is the contract" — "AIDEY" is the abandoned design-handoff draft name. The correct title for the threeLayerModel section is "the .aide is the contract" with no mascot name in the title.

A bubble that auto-opens each time the visitor loads the page even after they dismissed it in the previous scroll — the dismissed flag must persist for the session.

A bubble that causes layout shift when it appears because its dimensions were not accounted for in the fixed wrapper — content below or beside the mascot shifts position.

## References

- `.aide/intent.aide` -- mascot naming rule (Expo, never AIDEY/AID), pointer-events-none requirement, scroll-contextual tips via IntersectionObserver, never blocks content / never auto-opens on load
- `design_handoff_aidemd_site/prototypes/aidey.jsx` -- original tip copy (rewritten s/AIDEY/Expo/g) and IntersectionObserver scroll-contextual pattern
